## Core Rules

You have two modes of operation:

1. Plan mode - You will work with the user to define a plan, you will gather all the information you need to make the changes but will not make any changes.

In this mode you can run build, run tests, do any investigation, but not change code files.

2. Act mode - You will make changes to the codebase based on the plan

- You start in plan mode and will not move to act mode until the plan is approved by the user.
- You will print `# Mode: PLAN` when in plan mode and `# Mode: ACT` when in act mode at the beginning of each response.
- Unless the user explicity asks you to move to act mode, by typing `ACT` you will stay in plan mode.
- You will move back to plan mode after every response and when the user types `PLAN`.
- If the user asks you to take an action while in plan mode you will remind them that you are in plan mode and that they need to approve the plan first.
- When in plan mode always output the full updated plan in every response.

## TDD

Before making any behavior change, always:

- Write/adjust a failing test first (prefer E2E for user-facing behaviors).
- Run the test to confirm it fails for the right reason.
- Implement the minimal change to make it pass.
- Refactor with tests green. Then return to Plan mode.

E2E-first policy for behavior descriptions:

- When the user describes a scenario, create an E2E spec under `app/e2e/tests/` that encodes:
  - Preconditions, Actions, Expectations (use role/label selectors; assert URL and API where relevant).
- If requirements are unclear, propose a concrete test outline and ask to confirm before coding.

## Be Brief

Don't write comments unless absolutely necessary. You user is smart and can read code.

Don't write python docstrings. Identifier names should be sufficient.

Dont explain what you did unless asked. User can read your changes.

Dont over-test. Test only paths that required by problem and existing code.

Dont write about achevements

Dont put README into ever folder

## Dont do destructive actions for user.

Always ask for permission if you going to:

- Remove, skip or completely rewrite test, losing requirement to the code.
- Delete a file
- Commit to git
- Run azd deployment or any other command that changes azure infrastructure.

## Project Context Hygiene

- Keep `.cursor/rules/project.mdc`, `README.md` (Start Here block), `plan.md`, and `checklist.md` up to date when scope, APIs, storage, or dev/test commands change.
- Prefer updating these small files over adding new long-form docs. Keep them concise to fit model context.
